[2]
Date: Mon 24 May 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: BBC News online, Sun 23 May 2004 [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/3741137.stm>

New strain of Ebola virus responsible for outbreak in southern Sudan
-----------------------------------------------
Teams of international scientists are traveling to southern Sudan,
following an outbreak of a new strain of the deadly Ebola virus. World
Health Organization officials have traced an Ebola-like disease to the town
of Yambio, in the Western Equatorial region of south Sudan. 15 cases of the
potentially fatal virus have been confirmed over the past fortnight, and 4
people have died. More than 100 others are being kept under surveillance. 4
people are in isolation at Yambio Hospital, so the total infected could
still rise.
Previous major outbreaks of Ebola hemorrhagic fever [caused by different
strains of Ebola virus] have occurred in several parts of Africa: 1976 -
southern Sudan, 117 deaths; 1976 - Congo, 280 deaths; 2000 - northern
Uganda, 173 deaths; 2002 - Congo, 100 deaths.
The Ebola virus, in its early stages, is hard to diagnose, because some of
the symptoms, such as fever and joint pain, mimic malaria. Many people go
on to develop internal bleeding, a characteristic typical of Ebola
hemorrhagic fever, and without medical attention, the prospects are bleak.
A crisis group has been set up with aid agencies in the region in an
attempt to curtail the spread of the disease. The last major outbreak was
in Uganda 2 years ago; hundreds died. The hope is that quick action now
will avert a similar crisis in southern Sudan.
[Byline: Karen Allen]
